abitational name for someone from a place called Dobrów, named with the nickname   Dobry   ‘good’ + the possessive suffix <i>-ów</i>.","Polish: variant of   Dombrowski   or <b>Dąbrowski</b> (see   Dabrowski  )."]},{"name":"Dobrick","meanings":["Americanized form of Slovak <b>Dobrík</b>: nickname meaning ‘the good one’ (see   Dobry  ).","Americanized form of Serbian and Croatian <b>Dobrić</b> (see   Dobric  ).","German (of Slavic origin): nickname from a Germanized derivative of Old Slavic <i>dobrъ</i> ‘good’, or a habitational name from a place in Lusatia named Dobrig (<i>Dobrik</i> in Upper Sorbian). See also 4 below and compare   Dobrich  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice d'Oyry was born about 1235, in England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Piers d'Oyré. She married Jean Brienne de Beaumont Vicomte de Beaumont after 26 September 1265. She died about 1299, at the age of 66."},"et":{"about 1235–about 1299":"umbes 1235–umbes 1299","1235–1299":"1235–1299","1267–1323":"1267–1323","1260–1310":"1260–1310","1289–1330":"1289–1330","1289–1329":"1289–1329","1290–1350":"1290–1350","1244–1303":"1244–1303","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1260":"12